-- BHP Billiton, Rio Tinto, Energy Resources, Newcrest: Australia, NZ Stocks
-- B y   S h a n i   R a j a   a n d   M o n a m i   Y u i
-- 2010-10-14T05:32:00Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-10-14/bhp-billiton-rio-tinto-energy-resources-newcrest-australia-nz-stocks.html
Australia’s  S&P/ASX 200 Index  rose
1.7 percent to 4,699.10 at the close of trading in Sydney. New
Zealand’s  NZX 50 Index  increased 1 percent to 3,262.60 in
Wellington.  The following were among the most active shares in the
market today. Stock symbols are in parentheses after company
names.  Mining shares: Copper in London and New York climbed to the
highest levels in 27 months as a weaker dollar boosted demand
for commodities as alternative investments. China, the world’s
largest user of copper, said yesterday its foreign-exchange
reserves climbed by a record last month.  BHP Billiton Ltd.  (BHP AU), the world’s largest mining
company, gained 2.1 percent to A$41.66.  Rio Tinto Group  (RIO AU), the world’s third-biggest miner,
rose 4.4 percent to A$82.08.  Fortescue Metals Group Ltd.  (FMG AU) jumped 1.3 percent to
A$6.38. Chief Executive Officer  Andrew Forrest  may step back and
become non-executive chairman of the iron-ore producer after the
board meets next month to approve studies on its two expansion
projects, the Australian Financial Review reported, without
saying where it got the information.  Oil producers: Crude for November delivery climbed 1.6
percent to settle at $83.01 a barrel on the New York Mercantile
Exchange yesterday, the highest level since Oct. 6.  Woodside Petroleum Ltd.  (WPL AU), Australia’s second-
biggest oil and gas producer, rose 1.5 percent to A$44.39.
 Santos Ltd.  (STO AU) rallied 0.9 percent to A$12.84.  Gold producers: Gold rose to a record yesterday for the
15th time in the past month as the slumping dollar boosted
investor demand for the metal as an alternative investment.  Newcrest Mining Ltd.  (NCM AU), Australia’s largest gold
producer, climbed 3.3 percent to A$42.52.  St. Barbara Ltd.  (SBM
AU) advanced 7.2 percent to 44.5 Australian cents.  Amcor Ltd.  (AMC AU) gained 2.9 percent to A$6.45.
Australia’s biggest packaging company said there’s scope to
achieve more than A$250 million ($248 million) in annual savings
from its purchase of parts of Rio Tinto’s Alcan unit, the
Australian Financial Review reported, citing unnamed executives.  Eastern Star Gas Ltd.  (ESG AU) climbed 3.6 percent to 87.5
Australian cents. The coal-seam gas  said it signed an agreement
with Marubeni Corp. (8002 JT) that will advance plans to develop
its proposed liquefied natural gas project in Australia’s New
South Wales state.  Energy Resources of Australia Ltd.  (ERA AU) slid 0.7
percent to A$13.44, after having its stock rating cut by at
least four brokerages.  Qantas Airways Ltd.  (QAN AU) increased 1.1 percent to
A$2.89. Jetstar, a unit of the Australia’s biggest airline,
signed a commercial pact with American Airlines Inc., according
to an e-mailed statement from the Australian carrier.       Transurban Group  (TCL AU), the toll-road operator, lost 0.4
percent to A$5.17 after having its rating cut to “hold” from
“buy” by analysts led by  Marie Miyashiro  at Citigroup Inc.  To contact the reporter for this story:
